{"/service/ndnp/wa/batch_wa_hoh_ver01/data/sn87093220/00200290392/1907111401/0715.xml":{"full_text":"The HERALD is the Most Widely\nRead Paper on Crays Harbor\nABERDEEN HERALD\nVOL. XXII\nSKIES AHE CLEARING\nFINANCiAL CLOUDS ROLLING BY\nIN THE EAST.\nThe Mississippi Valley Lumberman\nof November S, on the Financial\nSituation in That Region. A Plan\nProposed to Eliminate Peeling ot\nDistrust of Banks.\nDuring the past week there lias\nbeen a considerable change in the j\nbusiness outlook. A week ago there\nwas much gloom in spite of the fact\nthat clear-headed people knew there\nwas nothing in general conditions\nthroughout the country that usually\naccompany business depression, or\ncauses it. Today the feeling is hope\nful because that fact has been rec\nognized by most people, and because\nbusiness has in a measure adjusted\nitself to the new order inaugurated\nby the banks. Money is more plen\ntiful and there is a greater disposi\ntion to permit it to circulate. The\nprompt action of the secretary of the\ntreasury in depositing government\nmoney in the large financial centers\nand the large imports of gold from\nabroad have supplied currency for\nthe necessary cash transactions in\nthe east, and the equally prompt ac\ntion on the part of the secretary of\nthe treasury in notifying the New\nYork banks that they were expected\nto utilize a portion of the government\nmoney deposited with them in meet\ning their obligations due Western\nand Northwestern banks, has started\n\u00abnough currency westward to Insure\nthe prompt handling of the crops.\nMuch more business has been\ntransacted during the past two weeks\nby use of cashiers' checks and clear\nng house certificates than ever before\nand the country has learned that it\ncan be done in this manner with com\nparatively little Inconvenience. In\nfact, It has been demonstrated that\nmuch business that has been trans\nacted In other ways can be done bet\nter by the use of these certificates.\nThe system should be continued be\ncause of its convenience. There is\nno reason why grain and other fiirm\nproducts should not be paid for in\nthis manner. The paper could be\nused by the farmer either for deposit\nIn his bank or for the purchase of\nsupplies from the country merchant,\nwho could deposit it in the bank or\nuse it in remitting for his goods pur\nchased from the city wholesaler. This\nwould do away with much of the\ntransfer of currency balances be\ntween the country and the city\nbanks. 'It would lessen the demand\nfor actual money and leave plenty\nof the real currency available at all\ntimes for use where Its use is abso\nlutely necessary.\nSince the money stringency com\nmenced many plans for currency re\nform have been proposed and many\nechemcs for avoiding similar (roubles\nin the future have been exploited. It\nIs generally recognized that much\ntrouble could be avoided if distrust\nof banking institutions could be elim\ninated. Incident to the recent fin\nancial flurry were the runs on a num\nber of savings banks and banks of\nother kinds because the people lost\nconlldence. In some instances this\nloss of faith was apparently war\nranted. When the officers of such\ninstitutions can use the bank funds\nfor speculative purposes, no matter\nhow large the surplus, the institution\nis not entirely worthy of trust.\nHence any plan that will guarantee\nto the people that these Institutions\nwill meet their obligations will tend\nto eliminate this distrust.\nIn the Piece Stuff department this\nweek will be found an Interview with\na gentleman who proposes a plan\nthat will guarantee safety to all de\npositors. It is nothing more nor less\nthan the formation by the banks of a\nguaranty company that will absolute\nly Insure the obligations of every one\nof its member banks. The principle\nwould be practically the same as that\nThis Is a Prescription Drug Store\nwitli long experience and training in the dispensing of pre\nscriptions. All that science can do or money can buy goes\nto make the service perfect ior your protection. May we fill\nyour prescription? Onr prices are low for the service given.\nRed Cross Pharmacy\nOpen All Night Phone 611\nunder which bonding companies op\nerate, and each bank would pay pre\nmiums in the ratio of its deposits or\nother obligations. This guaranty\ncompany would be responsible and\nwould therefore exercise the most\nrigid supervision of the banks that\nwere members of it. This would in\nsure much closer inspection of bank\ning practices than is now possible\nunder the system of bank examina\ntions. Instances have been known\nwhere allied banking institutions\nhave transferred securities and other\ncollateral, according as one or the\nother was being examined. The pro\nposed plan would make this impossi\nble. In case any bank was likely to\nfail to meet its obligations, the guar\nanty company would immediately\ntake charge and either straighten out\nits affairs or pay its obligations and\nwind them up. To this the propone\nent would provide for temporary\nmoney stringency by permitting the\nbanks to issue a form of currency se\ncured by approved bonds, but subject\nto a tax large enough to insure its\nspeedy retirement as soon as the\nemergency had passed.\nWEDDING Of* EDITH DENT.\nNuptials of Young Lady Well Known\non Grays Harbor.\nFollowing from tbe Alameda, Cal.,\nDaily Argu\u00df, of November 7, will greatly\ninterest many readers of the Hekalo\nTbe home of Mr. and Mrs. J. F. Soule,\nof 1801 Central avenue, was the acene\nlast night of one of the prettiest wed\nding that lias ever been celebrated in\nany of our Alameda homes, when Edith\nDurley Dent, daughter of Mrs. Soule,\nwas married to Lionel A. Wolff, a promi\nnent business man of San Francisco, but\nwidely known in the Northwest.\nThe house was a bower of yellow and\nwhite chrysanthemums, ferns, buckle\nberry and potted plants, and the ipacioua\nrooms were filled with exquisitely\nttowned women, amid which the bride,\nwith her blond beauty in dazzling white\nwedding gown shone resplendent.\nDuring the ceremony, which was per\nformed by Rev. William Norman Gurh\nrie, Clement Howlonds, who is a brother\nin-law of Mr. Wolff, sang 0, Promise\nMe,\" which was a very attractive feature\nof the service.\nMiss Maud Campbell, of San Jose, was\nthe maid cf honor, and Paul T. Carroll\nattended the bridegroom. She bride was\ngiven away by J. F. Soule.\nThere were about a hundred guests,\nand a delicious supper from Mandler's\nwas served. Dancing was a feature of\nthe evening, the house beitig particularly\nadapted to this amusement, into which\neveryone entered with spirit, making it\na jolly wedding throughout.\nA delightful trip has been* planned of\na three months' visit to Eastern cities,\nafter which Mr. and Mrs. Wolff will lo\ncate in some one of the suburban towns\nnear San Francisco.\nrOR GOOD ROADS.\nDelegates to State Convention Meet\nat licllingliam.\nBelunoiiam, Nov. 11. \u2014Fifty delegates\nfrom nil the counties in the state are in\nattendance at the sixth annual conven\ntion of the Washington Good Koads as\nsociation, which opened here today.\nThe meeting was opened this morning by\nPresident Samuel H. Hill. The visitors\nwere welcomed by Mayor A. L. Black,\nwho was responded to by Governor Mead,\nwho advocated the extension of the con\nvict labor system in state road building.\nJames McDonald, president of the Ameri\ncan Rjad Makers' association and high\nway commissioner of Connecticut, talked\nthis afternoon on \"State Aid in Connecti\ncut.\"\nJudge C. H. Hnnford, of the federal\ncourt, spoke on \"The Judiciary and\nHighways,\" in which be urged the con*\n(truction of a boulevard from Britiab\nColombia to Mexico.\nThe delegates from Cbebalia county\nare G. M. Powell, Aberdeen, and H. S.\nShorey, Montesano.\nA Business Chance.\nFor Sale\u2014Racket store in one of the\nbest towns in the Graya Harbor country.\nLong lean. Clean stock. Less than in\nvoice. Address K. 0., Hkrald office,\nAberdeen. 15-2 m\nSBMI WEEKLY\nABERDEEN, WASHINGTON, THURSDAY. NOVEMBER 14. 1907.\nALLEGED MURDERER\nOF FRANK TOOD IS ARRESTED AT\nHOQUIAM.\nHerbert Norman alias Ralph W. Steele,\nis Accused of the Brutal Crime.\nInfatuation for Mrs. Todd Said to\nHave Led to the Slaughter of Her\nHusband.\nDecoyed by Mrs. Todd, widow\noE the man he is Alleged to have\nmurdered, Ralph W. Steele has\nbeen taken into custody by the\nchieE oE police ol Hoqtjiam. It is\nunderstood that, acting under in\nstructions oE the ciiieE, the widow\naccepted Steele's requests for meet\nings, which he supposed were\nclandestine, but at which bis con*\nversations were overheard. The\nwoman is said to have so played\nupon bis feelings that, finally, he\nbroke down and confessed to her in\ndetail the murder of her husband\nHerbert Norman, alius Ualph VV.\n1 Steele, wm arrested Monday night at\nHoqaiam for the murder of Frank Todd,\nthe well-known woodsman, who waa\nit cruelly slain in his own woodshed on the\nnight of Augnst 31, 1907. From the mo\nment the murder was reported Steele\na was suspected and placed under surveil\nlance.\ni The murder of Todd attracted wide\ni spread attention as one of the most myt\nterious crimes ever committed in this\ncounty. That Todd was killed by some\nt one acquainted with the surroundings\nand bis habits was (be theory of the\n1 officials, and for two months prominent\ndetectives worked on the case, but tbe\ni perpetrator left no clue. Recently the\nr local police force of Hoquiem publicly ex\noneratud Steele for the purpose of throw\ni tag him off his guard, and what he Las\nbetrayed to cause his arrest is not known.\nIt is alleged that the person who at*\ntempted to murder Marshal McKenney\nSunday morning after sending him a de\ni coy telephone call, and shooting at him\ni from ambush, was Steele. The revolver\nfound on his person was a 38-caliber and\ni the (hells were loaded with black pow\n-1 der. Nothing concerning the evidence\ni secured by tbe police force could be\nlearned except that Marshal McKenney\nsaid to a reporter:\n\"Steele is ariested for murder and we\n1 have enough evidence to hang him. The\nevidence is conclusive and there has\nbeen no mistake made.\"\nSteele was formerly a lodger at the\nTodd home, and was madly infatuated\nwith Mrs. Todd, and had been driven\nfrom the house by the murdered man at\nthe point of a gun. Since the release of\nSteele Mrs. Todd lias been working with\nMarshal McKenney to entrap the sus\npect, and is said to have secured his ad\nmission to the crime, saying it was done\nout of love for her.\nMarshal McKenney, after being closet\ned with Mrs. Todd and Prosecuting At\ntorney Boner for live hours Tuesday\nmade tbe following statement:\n\"Mrs. Todd has undergone a most\nterrible ordeal and has done so under my\ninstructions. She has met Norman by\nappointment and has carried out in de\ntail everything asked of her. Words\ncannot describe the terror and awfulness\nof her position, for in communicating\nwitn Norman she realized the position it\nplaced her in with those who knew of it,\nand that means the general public, foi\nit was common talk. Could the public\nknow the exact circumstances of this\ncase their sympathy would go out to her.\nIt is one thing to have a strong suspicion\nof a man's guilt and another to get con\nclusive evidence\n\"At the time of the murder Mrs. Todd\ndid not know who killed her husband,\nand after Norman confessed to her, still\nmore evidence was necessary, and to get\nthis required many days and nights of\nplanning and watching with Mrs. Todd\ndoing all in her power to place in my\nbands the necessary evidence.\"\nToo much credit cannot be itiven Mar\nshal McKenney for his brilliant work in\nthis case. At bis request, Mrs. Todd\nnerved herself to make appointments and\nmeet the slayer of her husband, pretend\ning an acquiescence to his love-making\nuntil ilie wrunu from him a confession\nof the crime and his life history, McKen\nney always being an unseen witness at\nthose meetings.\nThe prosecution claims to have suffi\ncient testimony to send Steele to the\nfallows, but are properly reticent about\nits natute, so much so that no prelimin\nary examination was held in the justice's\ncourt, but the accused was taken to the\ncounty jail yesterday, and an information\ncharging him with murder will be filed\ndirect in the superior court, and the trial\nmay take place at the jury term of court\nin December.\nTHE ASSET CUR\nRENCY SCHEME\nFINANCIAL STRINGENCY WILL BE\nUSED TO URGE IT.\nThe Scheme Pushed for Years by the\nFrenzied financiers, Who Brought\non the Present flurry, will be\nUrged in Congress as a Panacea\nfor Panics.\nThere Is such a similarity between\nthe editorials in the city dailies de\nmanding an asset Currency as to sug\ngest that the editorials are written\nin response to a suggestion from the\nmoney centers, says Bryan's Com\nmoner. The big financiers have\neither brought on the present string\nency to compel the government to au\nthorize an asset currency or they\nhave promptly taken advantage of\nthe panic to urge the scheme which\nthey have had in mind for years.\nSeveral years ago Secretary Shaw\nstated that we must either have a\nperpetual debt or the bank notes\nwould have \"some other basis.\" The\n\"some other basis\" referred to is the\nasset basis. When it became apparent\nthat the public would not tolerate an\nasset currency the financiers asked\nfor an emergency currency based on\nassets. This was only a subterfuge\nand the republican leaders were\nafraid to press it at the last session.\nNow it is to be brought forward as\nif it were a new remedy, just thought\nof as a panic cure. It Is a panic\nbreeder instead of a panacea; it\nwould aggravate rather than relieve\nthe situation. It would increase the\nbank's liabilities just at a time when\ndepositors are fearful that the bank\ncan not meet present liabilities. The\nneed of elasticity has been very much\nexaggerated; if banks would prepare\nin advance for \"moving crops\" and\nfor such other future demands as may\nreasonably expected they would not\nbe confronted by so many \"emergen\ncies.\" The trouble is that they loan\nto the limit in ordinary times and\ntherefore have no reserve available\nfor the unusual demands. Another\ntrouble is that the banks are en\ncouraged to keep a large part of their\nreserve in reserve cities and there\nfore a shock in any of the big cities\ndisturbs banking everywhere. Just\nnow the country banks can not use\ntheir reserves because the big city\nbanks will not allow deposits to be\nwithdrawn.\nWhen the same money is counted\nover and over in the reserves of sev\neral banks the withdrawal of one\nthdusand dollars results in shrinkage\nof several times that sum.\nThe democrats should be on their\nguard ami resist this concerted de\nmand for an asset currency. It\nwould simply increase Wall Street's\ncontrol over the nation's finances and\nthat control is tyrannical enough\nnow. Such elasticity as is necessary\nshould be contr6lled by the govern\nment and not by the banks. The gov\nernment could furnish a certain\namount of elasticity by increasing\nand decreasing government deposits\naccording to the needs of business;\nor it could provide for the temporary\nissue of treasury notes on govern\nment bonds whenever a holder of\nbonds is willing to surrender the in\nterest; or it could issue treasury\nnotes in any emergency. But none\nof these plans will suit the finan\nciers; they insist upon absolute con\ntrol of the nation's finances\u2014they to\nreap the advantage while the public\nbears the burden and takes the\nchances.\nBut the democrats in the senate\nand house are in duty bound to look\nat the questiton from the standpoint\nof the people, and oppose the asset\ncurrency in whatever form it may\nappear. They may also have to op\npose the great central bank, which is\na part of a scheme of the financiers.\nAnd they will find that the same in\nfluences which are behind the asset\ncurrency and the central bank are\nbehind the president's plan for na\ntional incorporation of railroads.\nThey are all a part of plutocracy's\nplan to increase its hold upon the\ngovernment.\nWhat we need just now is not an\nemergency currency but greater se\ncurity for depositors. The depositors\nare scared \u2014unnecessarily scared in\nmost cases\u2014but scared. The govern\nment Is going to recommend a postal\n(Continued on pae four}\nGood\nflotSary Co. Luck\nKSKUSMA, WIS.\nBlack Cats bring good luck \u2014we have tl e\nBlack Cat Hosiery\u2014for ladies, boys and girls.\nThey will bring-you good luck\u2014try them.\nBEST EVER\nWe just received a new line of Rugs\u2014all\nstyles and sizes. They are beautiful and reason\nable.\nIF YOU HAVE\nA\nBANK ACCOUNT\ngive us your checks, otherwise every dollar of\nClearing 1 House Certificates will buy just as much\nand more than Uncle Sam's dollars.\nDON'T KICK\nand growl about a panic; there will be no panic.\nWe'll have better times than ever.\nBOOST\nand you'll be happy and make others feel happy.\nThat's the religion at\nGEO. J. WOLFF'S\nAberdeen's Largest and Best Store\nJOHN HANSON\nmerchajn t tailor\nFIRST IN FASHIONS, FIT AND VALUES\nWORKMANSHIP GUARANTEED\n2082 South G St, Aberdeen\nClearing House Certificates\nARE GOOD WITH US\nFor Goods or Cash\nGEO. FISHER\nThe Reliable Clothier 41 1 East Heron St*\nCertificates Are Gold\nReoelved am auoh, and mro redeemable In\nOold Depomlt them with u\u00bb on your Saving\u2022\nAooount and get 4per oent. compound Interest\nmame am on any other kind of U* S. money*\nAdvertisers Who Would Accom\nplish Results, Realize It.\nNo. 19","height":"27124","width":"19184"}}
